==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hap
<hw>Hap</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧p)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>happen</ets>.]</ety> <def>To clothe; to wrap.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The surgeon <qex>happed</qex> her up carefully.</q> <rj><qau>Dr.
J. Brown.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hap
<hw>Hap</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Hap</er> to clothe.]</ety>
<def>A cloak or plaid.</def> <mark>[O. Eng. & Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hap
<hw>Hap</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>happ</ets> unexpected good
luck. ⟦root⟧39.]</ety> <def>That which happens or comes suddenly or
unexpectedly; also, the manner of occurrence or taking place; chance;
fortune; accident; casual event; fate; luck; lot.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whether art it was or heedless <qex>hap</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cursed be good <qex>haps</qex>, and cursed be they that build⟦br⟧
Their hopes on <qex>haps</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P.
Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Loving goes by <qex>haps</qex>:⟦br⟧
Some Cupid kills with arrows, some with traps.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hap
<hw>Hap</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>happen</ets>. See
<er>Hap</er> chance, and cf. <er>Happen</er>.]</ety> <def>To happen; to
befall; to chance.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sends word of all that <qex>haps</qex> in Tyre.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ha'penny</ent>⟦br⟧
